<ArticleLayout
  title="Laundry Storage That Keeps Everyday Items Within Reach"
  seoTitle="Laundry Storage Planning for Australian Homes"
  description="Practical laundry organisation ideas for sorting, drying and storage, with checks for machine access, cleaning supplies and awkward spaces."
  category="Laundry"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-19"
  readingTime="6 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/laundry.webp"
  imageAlt="A practical laundry room with warm finishes, baskets and tidy everyday storage"
>
  <p>
    A laundry can look short of storage when the real problem is the route through it. A basket
    sits in front of the machine, wet clothes wait for the only airer and detergent gathers on
    the tub because the cupboard is awkward to reach.
  </p>
  <p>
    Watch one load move from bedrooms to machine, drying space and wardrobe before buying
    anything. That short exercise shows whether the room needs a hamper, a drying solution,
    safer cleaning-product storage or simply less clutter.
  </p>
  <p>
    The aim is not to fill every gap. It is to remove the points of friction while keeping
    appliances, plumbing, doors and walkways accessible. In a compact laundry, clear floor
    space often earns its place more convincingly than another organiser.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with the bottleneck</h2>
  <p>
    Different problems call for different storage. If dirty clothes collect in several rooms,
    review the hamper system. If wet washing has nowhere to go, protect drying space before
    adding shelves. If detergent and sprays have taken over the tub, group them and measure
    the bottles before choosing a caddy or cupboard insert.
  </p>
  <p>
    A narrow trolley can be useful beside a machine, but only if it rolls out past the
    skirting, hoses and door. A larger hamper may hold more, but not if it is unpleasant to
    carry through the hallway. Name the problem in one sentence before comparing products.
  </p>

  <h2>Match the storage to the job</h2>
  <div class="advice-stack">
    <section>
      <h3>Collecting and sorting</h3>
      <p>
        One carry basket may be enough for a household that sorts at the machine. Families
        that already separate towels, uniforms or workwear may benefit from a divided hamper.
        Capacity matters, but so do handle comfort, ventilation and a permanent parking spot.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Drying</h3>
      <p>
        Measure an airer fully open and folded. It needs enough room to stay open until the
        load is dry without blocking a door, appliance or main walkway. Indoor drying also
        needs useful airflow and a sensible surface beneath anything likely to drip.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Cleaning supplies</h3>
      <p>
        Remove empty or duplicate products, then group what remains by use. Keep chemicals in
        their original containers, follow the label and store them securely away from children
        and pets. A portable caddy suits supplies carried between rooms; a stable cupboard or
        shelf may suit products that stay in the laundry.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Small rooms and rentals</h3>
      <p>
        Freestanding shelves, portable racks and compact baskets are usually easier to adapt
        than fixed systems. Renters should check their agreement before drilling, and should
        not assume an adhesive product will leave paint, tiles or cabinetry unmarked.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <h2>Measure the room in working mode</h2>
  <p>
    Open the room door, appliance doors, top-loader lid and cupboards. Put the usual basket
    where it lands. A measurement taken from an empty wall is of little use if the proposed
    shelf occupies the space needed to unload the machine.
  </p>

  <h3>Around the washing machine and dryer</h3>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>appliance width, depth and height</li>
    <li>the space needed behind the appliance for hoses, taps and connections</li>
    <li>full lid or door clearance</li>
    <li>access to filters, vents, power points and controls</li>
    <li>the space needed to clean, maintain or move the appliance</li>
    <li>any movement during the spin cycle</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Top loaders need usable space above the machine; front loaders need it in front. Dryer
    placement, ventilation and stacking requirements vary, so follow the manufacturer's
    instructions rather than building storage tightly around the appliance.
  </p>
  <p>
    The dedicated guide to
    <a href="/guides/washing-machine-and-dryer-space-what-to-measure-before-buying-storage/">Australian laundry dimensions guide</a>
    covers side gaps, doors, hoses, filters and ventilation in more detail.
  </p>

  <h3>At the tub and under the sink</h3>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>internal cabinet width, depth and height</li>
    <li>the position of pipes, hoses, hinges and shut-off points</li>
    <li>the clear opening once the doors are open</li>
    <li>bottle height and the space needed to lift items out</li>
    <li>signs of moisture, leaks or damaged cabinet material</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Pipes divide the space into irregular pockets, so measure each usable section rather than
    relying on the cabinet's outside dimensions. Organisers should lift out easily and must not
    hide plumbing that needs inspection or access.
  </p>

  <h3>Across the floor and walls</h3>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>the clear walkway with every door open</li>
    <li>the route used to carry a full basket</li>
    <li>floor wastes, slopes, skirting and uneven surfaces</li>
    <li>wall material, tiles, services and fixing restrictions</li>
    <li>a comfortable reach height for everyday supplies</li>
    <li>the open and folded dimensions of any drying rack</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For fixed shelves, rails or racks, confirm the wall type, the product's fixing and load
    requirements, and whether drilling is permitted. Store heavy bottles below shoulder
    height and avoid placing anything where a fall or spill would land on a person or
    appliance.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose pieces that still work when full</h2>
  <p>
    Laundry storage has to cope with lint, moisture, spills and hurried wash days. Smooth,
    wipeable surfaces and enough clearance to clean around a unit are often more valuable than
    intricate compartments.
  </p>
  <p>
    Compare a product with the items it will hold. Record detergent bottle height, basket
    width, mop length, ironing-board size and the folded dimensions of the current airer. A
    shelf that fits the room but not the bottle is not a useful shelf.
  </p>
  <p>
    Also count the steps a system adds. Decanting, relabelling or sorting into six categories
    may look orderly, but it will fail if nobody maintains it. The best test is simple: can an
    item be returned with one hand while the other holds a basket?
  </p>

  <h2>Know when another organiser will not help</h2>
  <p>
    Empty bottles, duplicate cleaners, broken baskets and unused racks can make a storage
    shortage appear larger than it is. Move linen overflow, pet supplies and household items
    that do not support the laundry routine. Then reassess the space.
  </p>
  <p>
    Watch for solutions that create a second problem: a shelf that prevents the machine lid
    opening, a hamper that blocks the doorway, a trolley that cannot roll out, an airer with no
    folded home, or a wall rack installed without checking the wall and tenancy conditions.
  </p>
  <p>
    If clean clothes are living in baskets, the obstacle may be folding or putting away rather
    than storage for dirty washing. If the airer is always full, more cupboard capacity will
    not shorten the drying queue. Fix the stage that is actually failing.
  </p>

  <h2>Take this final list shopping</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>the exact routine problem the product will solve</li>
    <li>usable width, depth and height with doors and appliances open</li>
    <li>access to taps, hoses, filters, vents, power points and plumbing</li>
    <li>the product's dimensions when open, loaded and stored</li>
    <li>basket routes, walkway clearance and comfortable reach heights</li>
    <li>the size and weight of the items it will hold</li>
    <li>materials suited to the room's moisture and cleaning needs</li>
    <li>secure storage for chemicals, following their labels</li>
    <li>fixing, load and tenancy requirements for anything mounted</li>
    <li>a clear reason the existing setup cannot be rearranged instead</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The useful result is not a laundry that looks full of coordinated storage. It is a room
    where a basket can pass, every appliance opens properly and the next load has an obvious
    place to go.
  </p>

